That is the error that has mainly caused the VOD test on PS4 to be marked as "Partial Pass".

At the end of the VOD the error 02100 shows for a few seconds and then it disappears. During testing I was forcing the playback to reach to the end by using fast forward at x256. That is reproducible at all times.

Additionally, during exploratory testing around the VOD the Play Station error CE-34878-0 came up twice. That was happening when forcing the playback to a buffering state and play VOD and Live interchangeably.

Although the 02100 is a known issue for playstation (see https://jira.dev.bbc.co.uk/browse/IPLAYERTVV1-2476) the fact that the iPlayer caused Play Station to crash a few times would ideally require further investigation and closer monitoring.

That is the main reason that this test has been marked as "Partially Passed".

Following from that Test Case execution, some relevant exploratory testing has been performed (still by using stub data) and a pattern was found to force an instream error occuring from which the user cannot escape in an obvious way. In order for the pattern to occur the following steps should be followed:

***The below steps can be performed both on the device as well as on the Browser***

1. From the iPlayer main menu go to Categories and select the CBBC category
2. Under the CBBC category select any VOD to play 
3. On the error that occurs (that error will be happening at all times and for any VOD selected under this category; because of the stub data) click the dismissive button (it is an 'OK' button)
4. From the iPlayer main menu go to Channels and select BBC One
5. Click to play the 'On Now' Live program on BBC One
6. Immediately after going in the Live program click the 'Return' key on the remote control (or the 'Back' button on the browser's debug tools - if the testing is performed on the browser)
7. From the iPlayer main menu go to Home and play a VOD (the 'Arthur' VOD was played when the error occured during testing, but it should not make any difference if a different VOD is played)
8. The error '02100' is displayed on a blank (and black screen). Click any button on the remote control on the actual device. The error won't go away unless the 'Exit' button is clicked on the remote control of the device. (on the Browser even when the iPlayer's debugTools are used, there is no Exit button).


***I discussed the above with Praveen and Alphonsa. The explanation that the playback team has provided is that when trying to play a Live video (Steps 5 and 6 above), because of the way the stub data is created, it is searching for sub-titles and those cannot be found in the Live program. That is why when performing Step7 (playing a VOD from Home), the playback is failing because it is still trying to find the sub-titles from the previous instance.***

***It would be useful to keep an eye on that issue and ensure that it will not be reproducible anymore, after the stub data is updated/fixed, so that it is not looking for sub-titles in a Live program.***

As part of that testing, and after contacting a brief exploratory session which was about playing various VODs in Sports as well as in News, I noticed that there is an issue with the sound for various VODs that are played in Sports. A similar issue was also observed in News but the sound quality in Sports VODs was worst compared to that of the News. 

Specifically what I saw for the current device under test (the Samsung one) was:

Below Volume5 I could not hear anything and for some others VODs to be the Volume needed to be set at 7 or 8 just to start hearing something.

For example under <Wales> category when the VOD with title ‘Playing England a great opportunity’ is launched I can’t hear nearly anything even with the Volume at 7 - as the video was progressing it was getting slightly better.

The above observations were communicated to the test leads, and they believe that it is because of the assets themselves. They have also checked on another device, and they observed the same issue with the sound for VODs in Sports.
